metadata.name: THINK OUTSIDE THE BOX #53
metadata.description:
IMPORTANT: THE PIECES YOU MINT ARE NOT THE FULL ARTWORK.

This artwork relies on fxhash's gallery display to be viewed properly. It must be viewed with four pieces per line, and iterations from lowest to highest. You may need to resize the window to display the full project properly.

This piece is an experimental exploration of what lies beyond the canvas, told through counter-cultural slogans. Its nature is reflected in these chosen mottos, embodying the disdain for the old and the embrace of the new, unique and non-traditional style of this token. It's a call to arms for more avant-garde, experimental projects that push the limits of what we would currently consider generative art. Ignore the tried and true. Go against the grain. Think outside the box.

metadata.name: Automaton #269
metadata.description: An Elementary Cellular Automaton created with pure JavaScript. In this instance, the capability to invert the order of the rule has been added, and the drawing is performed from the bottom of the canvas to the top, resulting in a fresh perspective. Finally, a gradient is incorporated to accurately differentiate the states of the cells

metadata.name: Betty's Broken Loom #27
metadata.description: For decades Betty's fine hand woven fabrics were traded at markets around the small mountain towns. She's getting older now and her loom is broken but her love for weaving continues. Since the knits aren't perfect she's giving them away cheaply in hopes that others will find still find some use for them.

metadata.name: Snowflake #643
metadata.description:
This snowflake is created using a cellular automaton in a hexagonal grid. 

Each tile can be in a binary state of either being free or frozen. The next state is determined by assigning a random probability of freezing and thawing to each possible combination of frozen/free neighbouring tiles.

Some Snowflakes will die, some will find a stable state, some will loop but most of them will keep going forever.

Press space to pause/unpause.

For Free. 

Merry Christmas!

metadata.name: intermission #55
metadata.description:
'intermission' is an artwork that thats based on the distinct structuring of onethousendsixhundred circles. their arrangement within a calm defined pattern, leads to an effect of waviness with every generated color-palette.   while the pattern stays static, it’s the randomised colors which create a very unique character within every single generated piece.   

as i find there is a high number of great colorcombinations, i made the iteration number high, but the floor low.

 pressing 's' lets you save a .png file

if you like 'intermission' mint a piece or two, fall in love with its colors, spread the love!!!

metadata.name: Randos #160
metadata.description:
Meet Randos. Generative PFP ready pictures. Each Rando has unique features and a rando-id made up of a random 3 letter word + a number. See if you can get a scrabble-friendly word. Each Rando also has a frequently used word/phrase. Inspired by the Xcopy style flashing imagery, glitch art, and color pallete.


Click on the image to save a frame.
Please mint only a few as it's a free mint.

metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #45
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord. 

/////
Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd
